    "created_at": "2018-04-26T01:59:14Z",
    "updated_at": "2018-04-26T01:59:14Z",
    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "As I have been arguing elsewhere (so sorry if you have seen this one before), the only governance process that I think really matters/is effective is one of forking.  Building a forking governance layer on top of a forking governance layer feels redundant.  I would be pretty strongly against a democratic governance layer built on top of the current forking governance layer because ultimately, the only way users have to opt-out of a democratic system is to fork, so we are right back where we started with people forking Ethereum.\r\n\r\nI'm far less scared of a fork than I think a lot of people are.  I think forking should be easy and should happen fairly regularly.  It is unlikely that, as the userbase of Ethereum grows, everyone will continue to agree on everything and so if forks aren't happening that to me signals that forking is too hard.  Bitcoin has seen a number of forks lately, and I think this is healthy.  While I still think Bitcoin has a ton of problems shared across all of the forks, I don't think its forking is the problem.",
